From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Keeley Hammond <vertedinde@electronjs.org>
Date: Thu, 16 Jul 2026 01:29:42 +0000
Subject: fix: ignore non-occluding windows in the mac occlusion checker

The manual occlusion pass in WebContentsOcclusionCheckerMac only
compares window frames: any visible NSWindow above the target whose
frame contains it marks the target's web contents as occluded. Window
opacity is never consulted, so a transparent overlay (setOpaque:NO with
a clear background) or a click-through window (ignoresMouseEvents) is
counted as an occluder even though the content beneath it stays fully
visible. The covered renderer then flips to visibilityState "hidden"
and gets background-throttled.

Skip candidate occluders that are faded (alphaValue < 1), that ignore
mouse events, or that are non-opaque without an opaque background,
mirroring the checks the Windows tracker applies via
gfx::IsWindowVisibleAndFullyOpaque (WS_EX_TRANSPARENT and translucent
layered windows are ignored there).

This patch can be removed if the change is upstreamed to Chromium.

diff --git a/content/app_shim_remote_cocoa/web_contents_occlusion_checker_mac.mm b/content/app_shim_remote_cocoa/web_contents_occlusion_checker_mac.mm
index 54aaffde30c14a27068f89b6de6123abd6ea0660..b3cf6859b38dc43cf999aafdde84fac7cce9d053 100644
--- a/content/app_shim_remote_cocoa/web_contents_occlusion_checker_mac.mm
+++ b/content/app_shim_remote_cocoa/web_contents_occlusion_checker_mac.mm
@@ -414,6 +414,24 @@ - (void)performOcclusionStateUpdates {
   _updatingOcclusionStates = NO;
 }
 
+// Returns NO for windows that cannot visually obscure the windows beneath
+// them: faded windows, non-opaque windows without an opaque background
+// (e.g. an embedder's transparent overlay shows the covered content through
+// it) and windows that let mouse events pass through. This mirrors
+// gfx::IsWindowVisibleAndFullyOpaque, which the Windows occlusion tracker
+// uses to ignore translucent layered windows and WS_EX_TRANSPARENT windows.
+- (BOOL)windowCanOccludeOtherWindows:(NSWindow*)window {
+  if ([window alphaValue] < 1.0 || [window ignoresMouseEvents])
+    return NO;
+  if ([window isOpaque])
+    return YES;
+  // Non-opaque windows still hide what's beneath them as long as they paint
+  // an opaque background (embedders clear -isOpaque just to get rounded
+  // corners).
+  CGColorRef background = [[window backgroundColor] CGColor];
+  return background && CGColorGetAlpha(background) >= 1.0;
+}
+
 // Returns YES if `window` is occluded, either according to macOS or via
 // our manual occlusion calculation.
 - (BOOL)isWindowOccluded:(NSWindow*)window
@@ -456,6 +474,11 @@ - (BOOL)isWindowOccluded:(NSWindow*)window
       continue;
     }
 
+    // Skip windows that can't visually cover the web contents beneath them.
+    if (![self windowCanOccludeOtherWindows:nextWindow]) {
+      continue;
+    }
+
     // Ideally we'd compute the region which is the sum of all windows above
     // `window` and see if it completely contains `window`'s web contents.
     // Unfortunately, we don't have a library that can perform general purpose
